<center><b><font size="+2"><font color="red">r</font>etawq</font></b></center>

<p>Welcome to the home page of the <b>retawq project</b>. retawq is an
interactive, multi-threaded network client (<b>web browser</b>) for text
terminals on computers with Unix-like operating systems. It is written in C,
fast, small, nicely configurable, and comfortable; e.g. the low-level network
communications are performed in a non-blocking way, and you can keep open as
many "virtual windows" as you want and work simultaneously in two of them in a
split-screen mode. (<a href="docu/feature.html">Features Overview</a>)</p>

<p><b>Requirements:</b> a Unix-like operating system; a C compiler to build an
executable program from the source code (e.g. <a
href="http://directory.fsf.org/gcc.html">gcc</a>); recommended: a "curses"
library for terminal control (e.g. <a
href="http://directory.fsf.org/ncurses.html">ncurses</a>) and a pthreads (Posix
threads) library</p>

<p><b>Download</b> version 0.2.6c via <a
href="http://prdownloads.sourceforge.net/retawq/retawq-0.2.6c.tar.gz">HTTP
mirrors</a> or <a
href="ftp://ftp.sourceforge.net/pub/sourceforge/r/re/retawq/retawq-0.2.6c.tar.gz">FTP</a>
(released 19 March 2006; 384 KB; gzipped archive file containing source code
and <a href="docu/index.html">documentation</a>); <a
href="http://sourceforge.net/project/shownotes.php?release_id=402791&group_id=36148">release
notes</a>; <a
href="http://sourceforge.net/project/showfiles.php?group_id=36148">old
versions</a> (deprecated); <a href="CHECKSUMS">MD5 checksums</a>; <a
href="http://sourceforge.net/projects/retawq">general information</a></p>

<p>Platform-specific files and packages available at other locations: <a
href="http://ftp.gwdg.de/pub/linux/misc/suser-guru/rpm/packages/Network/retawq/">SuSE
RPMs</a> (Linux); <a
href="http://www.FreeBSD.org/cgi/ports.cgi?query=retawq">FreeBSD</a>; <a
href="http://darwinports.opendarwin.org/darwinports/dports/www/retawq/">Darwin
Ports</a> (Mac OS X)</p>

<p>retawq is used in the following distributions: <a
href="http://slimlinux.freezope.org/">slimlinux</a>; <a
href="http://www.minimalinux.org/ttylinux/">ttylinux</a>; <a
href="http://www.modest-proposals.com/Hacklin.htm">Xwoaf</a></p>

